DataElement.PREFERREDDEFINITION: The temperature of an individual derived in celsius.

DATAELEMENTCONCEPT.PreferredDefinition: The degree of hotness or coldness of a body or environment using the Celsius (Centigrade) scale.

VALUEDOMAIN.PreferredDefinition: The temperature of an individual derived in celsius.

DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Methods: Multiply value by 5/9, and subtract 32. Resultant value is displayed as derived temperature Celsius.
DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Rule: When temperature value is entered as a degrees Fahrenheit value, calculate and display as degrees Celsius.

ComponentDataElementsList_ITEM.PreferredDefinition: The body temperature expressed in Celsius degrees.
The participant"s temperature.

DataElement.LONGNAME: Examination Age in Derived Years Number
DataElement.PREFERREDDEFINITION: A person's age at the time of an examiniation, expressed as a derived number of years since birth.

DATAELEMENTCONCEPT.PreferredDefinition: A person's age at the time of an examiniation, usually stated in years since birth.

VALUEDOMAIN.PreferredDefinition: Number of years since birth, expressed as a concept of quantity derived from zero and units.

DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Methods: Round to the whole number, no decimals.
DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Rule: Examination age = Examination date - Date of patient/participant birth.

ComponentDataElementsList_ITEM.PreferredDefinition: The date of the evaluation, procedure or visit that yielded data.
the month, day and year on which the patient/participant was born.

DataElement.LONGNAME: Age At Death Derived in Years Number
DataElement.PREFERREDDEFINITION: Value to represent the age of a person at the time of death, expressed in number of years.

DATAELEMENTCONCEPT.PreferredDefinition: Age of a person at the time of death, stated in years since birth until death.

VALUEDOMAIN.PreferredDefinition: Patient age expressed in number of years since birth.

DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Methods: Subtract Birth date from Death date; divide by 365 to yield person age at the time of death.
DATAELEMENTDERIVATION.Rule: Age at death is the age (in years) of a person on the date of death.

ComponentDataElementsList_ITEM.PreferredDefinition: The actual date of a patient's/participant's death.
the month, day and year on which the patient/participant was born.

The addition of somebody or something to, or the presence of somebody or something in, a group or mixture, particularly, a passive, usually temporary, product of cell activity within the cytoplasm or nucleus.

DataElement.LONGNAME: Glaucoma Patient Self-Report Personal Medical History Yes or No Response
DataElement.PREFERREDDEFINITION: An ocular disease, occurring in many forms, having as its primary characteristics an unstable or a sustained increase in the intraocular pressure which the eye cannot withstand without damage to its structure or impairment of its function. The consequences of the increased pressure may be manifested in a variety of symptoms, depending upon type and severity, such as excavation of the optic disk, hardness of the eyeball, corneal anesthesia, reduced visual acuity, seeing of colored halos around lights, disturbed dark adaptation, visual field defects, and headaches. (Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed). Subjective reports made by a patient. An account of all medical events and problems a person has experienced. A caDSR representation term that is used to indicate a question with permissible values of yes/no

DATAELEMENTCONCEPT.PreferredDefinition: An ocular disease, occurring in many forms, having as its primary characteristics an unstable or a sustained increase in the intraocular pressure which the eye cannot withstand without damage to its structure or impairment of its function. The consequences of the increased pressure may be manifested in a variety of symptoms, depending upon type and severity, such as excavation of the optic disk, hardness of the eyeball, corneal anesthesia, reduced visual acuity, seeing of colored halos around lights, disturbed dark adaptation, visual field defects, and headaches. (Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed). Subjective reports made by a patient. An account of all medical events and problems a person has experienced.
